SIMPLE: nestle
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Nestle
<hw>Nes"tle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Nestled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Nestling</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS.
<ets>nestlian</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make and occupy a nest;
to nest.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The kingfisher . . . <qex>nestles</qex> in hollow banks.</q>
<rj><qau>L'Estrange.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To lie close and snug, as a bird in her nest; to
cuddle up; to settle, as in a nest; to harbor; to take
shelter.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Their purpose was to fortify in some strong place of the wild
country, and there <qex>nestle</qex> till succors came.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The children were <qex>nestled</qex> all snug in their beds⟦br⟧
While visions of sugarplums danced in their heads.</q> <rj><qau>Clement
Clarke Moore (A Visit From St. Nicholas, (a poem [1823]) also called The
<er>Night Before Christmas</er>).</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To move about in one's place, like a bird when
shaping the interior of her nest or a young bird getting close to the
parent; <as>as, a child <ex>nestles</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Nestle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Nestle
<hw>Nes"tle</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To house, as in a
nest.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To cherish, as a bird her young.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Nestling</ent>⟦br⟧
